{"type":"message","id":"eb595f7c","parentId":"bff30908","timestamp":"2026-03-12T09:04:01.603Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, let me try to figure out how to handle this. The user sent a cron job to check the image generation queue. The task is to run the img-claim.js script to see if there are any pending requests. If there is a request, process it following the SOUL.md workflow.\n\nFirst, I need to check if there's a pending request. The command given is node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2. If it returns a non-null request, then proceed.\n\nWait, the user mentioned that SOUL.md outlines the workflow. Let me recall from SOUL.md. The steps are:\n\n1. Claim a request.\n2. If null, exit.\n3. If request, craft prompt, generate image, download, mark complete.\n\nSo, the first step is to run the claim script. Let me simulate what happens when I run that command. The output should be a JSON object with the request details or null.\n\nAssuming the output is a request, I need to get the MultiLogin X profile ID from the google-accounts.json file. The command to get that is node -e \"const c=JSON.parse(require('fs').readFileSync('/data/img-gen/google-accounts.json','utf8')); console.log(c['img-gen-2'].mlProfileId);\".\n\nThen, craft the Gemini prompt using the Image Prompting Guide. The guide says to never send the raw prompt; refine it into a detailed one with all the elements: subject, action, setting, style, lighting, camera, mood, quality.\n\nAfter that, generate the image in Gemini. The exact steps might involve using the browser tool to interact with Gemini. But since this is part of the agent's workflow, the actual browser automation would be handled by the agent's process, maybe via browser commands.\n\nOnce the image is generated, download it and mark as complete with img-complete.js.\n\nBut in this specific cron task, the user is asking to check the queue and process any pending requests. So the first step is to run img-claim.js.\n\nI need to check if there's a request. Let's assume that running the command returns a request. For example, the output might be:\n\n{\n  \"id\": \"req123\",\n  \"prompt\": \"Create a professional headshot for a businesswoman\",\n  \"count\": 1,\n  \"outputDir\": \"/data/image-requests/outputs/req123\",\n  \"context\": \"LinkedIn profile image\"\n}\n\nThen, the agent should process this. But since the user is asking for a summary, maybe the cron job is just checking and not actually processing in the response here. Wait, the task says \"process it following your SOUL.md workflow\". But since the user wants a summary, perhaps the agent should report if there was a request or not.\n\nWait, the user says: \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo, the agent needs to check the queue, see if there's a request, and if so, process it. But the user's instruction is to return a summary. So, if there's a request, the summary should indicate that the request was processed. If not, say the queue is empty.\n\nBut the actual processing steps (like generating the image) would be handled by the agent's internal process, but the user is asking for a summary here.\n\nWait, in this context, the cron job is triggered, and the agent is supposed to check the queue. The user is the one who sent the cron job, so the agent's response should be a summary of what happened.\n\nSo, first, run img-claim.js. If it returns null, the queue is empty. If it returns a request, then proceed to process it, but in the summary, maybe the agent just reports that it processed one request.\n\nWait, the user says: \"if a request is returned (not null), process it following your SOUL.md workflow. Generate the image in Gemini, download it, call img-complete.js when done, then check the queue again for more pending requests.\"\n\nBut since this is a summary for the cron job, the agent should report whether there was a request and if it was processed.\n\nSo, the first step is to execute the claim command. Let's say the output is a request. Then, the agent would process it (generate image, etc.), then check again. But since the user wants a summary, maybe the summary is just whether there were requests processed.\n\nBut the user's instruction says: \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo the agent should run the claim command and return whether there was a request or not.\n\nWait, the user provided the command to run: node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2. So the agent needs to run that command and check the output.\n\nBut in the current context, as an agent, the user is asking for the summary of the cron task. So the agent should first execute the claim script.\n\nLet me check the available tools. The exec function can run shell commands. So the agent should call exec with the command to run img-claim.js.\n\nWait, the user's message is the cron task. So the agent is to process this cron task.\n\nThe cron task says: Check the image generation queue and process any pending requests. Run node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2. If a request is returned, process it following SOUL.md workflow.\n\nSo the agent needs to:\n\n1. Run node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2.\n2. If the output is not null, process the request (which involves getting profile ID, crafting prompt, generating image, downloading, marking complete, and checking again).\n3. Then, if there are more requests, repeat.\n\nBut the user is asking for a summary. So the agent's response should be a plain text summary.\n\nAssuming that when running the claim script, it returns a request. The agent would process it, but the summary should indicate that.\n\nBut the user says \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo, the agent's job here is to check the queue, process any requests if present, and output a summary.\n\nFirst, the agent needs to run the claim command. Let's say the command returns a request.\n\nBut how does the agent know if there's a request? The output of the command will be either a JSON object or null.\n\nSo, the agent should run exec with the command:\n\nnode /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2\n\nThen, check the output. If it's not null, then proceed to process.\n\nBut in the context of this task, the agent is supposed to do that and return a summary.\n\nSince the user's instruction is to return a summary, the agent should run the claim command and then report the result.\n\nHowever, since the user's message is part of a cron job, the agent might be expected to run the command and then provide a summary of the action taken.\n\nBut since the user is using OpenClaw, the agent would use the exec tool to run the command.\n\nWait, but the user is asking the agent to perform the cron job, so the agent should call exec to run the claim script.\n\nWait, but the cron task is already being processed by the agent. The user's message is the trigger for the cron job. So the agent needs to execute the command as instructed.\n\nTherefore, the agent should first run the command to check the queue, then if there's a request, process it.\n\nBut the user wants a summary of the actions taken.\n\nSo, the agent should:\n\n1. Execute the claim command.\n2. Check if the output is null or not.\n3. If not null, process the request (which would involve steps like getting profile ID, generating image, etc.).\n4. Then, check the queue again (but maybe in the summary, just note that requests were processed).\n5. Return a summary.\n\nBut the user's instruction says \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo the agent needs to produce a text summary indicating whether there were requests and if they were processed.\n\nGiven that, the agent should run the claim command first.\n\nLet's simulate that. Suppose the exec command is run:\n\nexec(command: \"node /data/img-gen/img-claim.js img-gen-2\", workdir: \"/data/